==English==

===Etymology===

From Old English '''[[absteynen]]''', '''[[abstenen]]''', from Old French '''[[astenir]]''', '''[[abstenir]]''', from Latin '''[[abstinere]]''', '''[[abstentum]]''', transitive and intransitive verb, ''keep or refrain from''; from prefix '''[[ab-]]''', '''[[abs-]]''', ''from'', + '''tenere''', ''hold''. See [[tenable]].

===Verb===
'''abstain''' ([[abstained]], [[abstaining]])

# refrain from (something); hold one's self [[aloof]]; to [[forbear]] or [[refrain]], especially from an [[indulgence]] of the passions or appetites; -- with ''from''.
#To shun voluntarily.
#:Quotations:  Not a few '''abstained''' from voting. - [[Macaulay]]
#:Quotations:  Who '''abstains''' from meat that is not gaunt? - Shakespeare, ''Richard II, II-i''
# {{intransitive}} Deliberately refrain from casting one's vote at a meeting where one is present.
# {{transitive}} hinder; [[withhold]].
#:Quotation:  Whether he '''abstain''' men from marrying. - [[Milton]]

